// Provide a fix for the buggy function.
Root cause: The root cause of this bug is that when the function getReadableJSTypeName encounters a GETPROP node and the object type is a constructor, it tries to find the property in the prototype chain of the object type. However, it doesn't correctly handle the case when the property is not found in the prototype chain and the object type is not the original type of the property, but rather a property of another object. This leads to the function returning a type name that includes the property name of the object that contains the original object, instead of just the original object's type name.
Suggestion: Keep Track of the Original Object Type
We can modify the getReadableJSTypeName function to keep track of the original object type when climbing the prototype chain. If we find the property in the prototype chain, we use the original object type to construct the type name. This can be achieved by storing the original object type in a variable before the while loop, and then using this variable to construct the type name when the property is found. The modified code would look like this:
```java
if (n.isGetProp()) {
    ObjectType objectType = getJSType(n.getFirstChild()).dereference();
    ObjectType originalObjectType = objectType; // Store the original object type
    if (objectType != null) {
        String propName = n.getLastChild().getString();
        if (objectType.getConstructor() != null &&
            objectType.getConstructor().isInterface()) {
            objectType = FunctionType.getTopDefiningInterface(
                objectType, propName);
        } else {
            // classes
            while (objectType != null && !objectType.hasOwnProperty(propName)) {
                objectType = objectType.getImplicitPrototype();
            }
        }

        // Don't show complex function names or anonymous types.
        // Instead, try to get a human-readable type name.
        if (objectType != null &&
            (objectType.getConstructor() != null ||
             objectType.isFunctionPrototypeType())) {
            return originalObjectType.toString() + "." + propName; // Use the original object type
        }
    }
}
